ai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1051119/asp/calcutta/story_5496713.asp | location=Calcutta, India | work=The Telegraph | title=Stage On & Off | date=2005-11-19}}</ref> ''The Big Fat City'' and<ref>TOI Bangalore News [https://www.flickr.com/photos/131725729@N05/16947113377/ \" The Murder that never was\"]</ref> ''The Murder That Never Was'', starring [[Dheiraj Kapoor]].\n\nHe is the first playwright in English to be awarded the [[Sahitya Akademi award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19981229/36351574.html|title=Sahitya Academy awards announced|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|author=PTI|date=1998-12-29|accessdate=2009-04-02}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> His plays have been directed by eminent directors like [[Arvind Gaur]], [[Alyque Padamsee]] and [[Lillete Dubey]].\n\n==Early life and background==\nMahesh Dattani was born in [[Bangalore]] to [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] parents.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/paradox-at-play/article6126322.ece|title=Paradox at play|first=Anjana|last=Rajan|date=18 June 2014|publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thethumbprintmag.com/drama-is-about-character-revelation-mahesh-dattani-dance-like-a-man/|title=Drama is about character revelation|publisher=The Thumb Print|date=1 November 2012}}</ref> He went to [[Baldwin Boys High School]] and then went on to join [[St. Joseph's College, Bangalore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mapsofindia.com/who-is-who/art-culture/mahesh-dattani.html|title=Mahesh Dattani|website=www.mapsofindia.com|access-date=2016-05-09}}</ref>\n\nDattani is a graduate in History, Economics and Political Science.<ref name=\"Mans World\">{{cite web| url=https://www.mansworldindia.com/currentedition/from-the-magazine/drama-mahesh-dattanis-life/| title=The Drama in Mahesh Dattani's Life| last=De| first=Aditi| publisher=[[Man's World (magazine)]]| access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He completed his post-graduate in Marketing and Advertising Management because he wanted to become a [[copywriter]].<ref name=\"Mans World\" />\n\nHe worked with the Bangalore Little Theatre, where his first role was in [[Utpal Dutt| Utpal Dutt's]] ``Surya Shikhar``\n\nAfter reading Edward Albee\u2019s play ''[[Who\u2019s Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]'' early in his life, he became interested in writing. He was also influenced by Gujarati playwright [[Madhu Rye]]\u2019s ''Kumarni Agashi'' and developed an interest in play writing.<ref>http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010114/spectrum/scene.htm</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMahesh Dattani began his career as a copywriter in an advertising firm. In 1986, he wrote his first full-length play, ''Where There\u2019s a Will'', and since 1995, he has been working as a full-time theatre professional. He has also worked with his father in the family business.\n\nDattani is also a film director. His debut film is ''Mango Souffle'', adapted from one of his plays. He also wrote and directed the movie ''[[Morning Raaga]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/fullstory.php?content_id=9285|title=Story teller|publisher=ScreenIndia|author=Bhawana Somaaya|authorlink=Bhawana Somaaya |date=2004-11-22|accessdate=2009-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Playwright ==\n* ''Where There's a Will'' (1988)\n* ''Dance Like a Man'' (1989)\n* ''Bravely Fought the Queen'' (1991)\n* ''Final Solutions'' (1993)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sites.google.com/site/asmitatheatre/reviews--final-solutions|title=Mahesh Dattani's Final Solutions|accessdate=2009-04-02|author=Drama critics}}</ref>\n* ''Do The Needful''\n* ''On a Muggy Night in Mumbai'' (1998)\n* ''Seven Circles Round The Fire'' (Radio play for BBC) (''Seven Steps around the Fire'') (1998)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CdoTAAAAQBAJ|title=Seven Steps around the Fire: A Radio Play|last=Dattani|first=Mahesh|date=2013-07-15|publisher=Penguin UK|isbn=9789351182153|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''The Murder That Never Was'' (2000)\n* ''[[30 Days in September (Play)|30 Days in September]]'' (2001)\n* ''The Girl Who Touched the Stars (2007)\n* ''Brief Candle'' (2009)\n* ''Where Did I Leave My Purdah'' (2012)\n* ''The Big Fat City'' (2012)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Director===\n* ''Mango Souffle''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2003/02/20/stories/2003022000780300.htm|title=Going bananas over Mango Souffle|publisher=The Hindu|author=Diwan Singh Bajali|date=2003-02-20|accessdate=2009-04-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[Morning Raga]]''\n* ''Dance Like a Man''\n* ''Ek Alag Mausam''\n\n== Awards ==\n* ''Dance Like a Man'' has won the award for the Best Picture in English awarded by the National Panorama in 1998\n* [[Sahitya Academy award]] for his book of plays ''Final Solutions and Other Plays''\n* [[Sahitya Kala Parishad]] selected ''Final Solutions'' (1997), ''Tara'' (2000) and ''30 Days in September'' (2007) as best productions of the year, directed by [[Arvind Gaur]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n9. G Baskaran, ed., Girish Karnad and Mahesh Dattani: Methods and Motives, Yking Books, Jaipur, 2012.\n\n==External links==\n* [[Bhattacharya, Anindya]]. \"Desire and the Postcolonial Nation\" in ''Seven Steps around the Fire'' and ''Final Solutions''. ''The Plays of Mahesh Dattani: An Anthology of Recent Criticism''. Ed. Tutun Mukherjee. [[New Delhi]]: Pencraft International, 2012 ({{ISBN|978-93-82178-03-3}}), pp.&nbsp;184\u2013196.\n* [[Roy, Pinaki]]. \"Mahesh Dattani's ''Final Solutions'': A Brief Rereading\". ''Mahesh Dattani: His Stagecraft in Indian Theatre''. Ed. Bite, V. [[New Delhi]]: Authors Press, 2013 ({{ISBN|978-81-7273-737-5}}), pp.&nbsp;111\u201324.\n* [[Das, B.K]]. \"Mahesh Dattani's ''Dance Like a Man'': A Thematic Study\". ''The Atlantic Literary Review 15.3 (2014)''. Ed. Rama Kundu. [[New Delhi]]: Atlantic Pub., 2014 ({{ISBN|978-81-269-2052-5}}), pp.&nbsp;73\u201380.\n* [[Das, B.K]]. \"In Search of Shakespearean Echoes in Mahesh Dattani: A Study of ''The Big Fat City'' as a Critique of Contemporary Urban Indian Society\". ''Yearly Shakespeare'' Vol. XIV (2016). Ed. Goutam Ghosal. [[Santiniketan]]: [[Sri Aurobindo Study Centre]],  2016 (ISSN 0976-9536), pp.&nbsp;60\u201369.\n* [[Das, B.K]]. \"The Tale of an Imperial Kin: Unfolding the East-West Problematic in Mahesh Dattani's ''The Tale of a Mother Feeding Her Child''\". World Journal of Gender & Literature 4.1 (June 2017). Ed. Lata Mishra. New Delhi: Authorspress, 2017 (ISSN 2349-1620), pp.&nbsp;135\u2013142.\n{{Sahitya Akademi Award for English}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dattani, Mahesh}}\n[[Category:21st-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Indian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sahitya Akademi Award in English]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n", "name_user": "AyushMukherjee376", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and background:add ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahesh_Dattani"}
{"title_page": "Kaliwa Low Dam", "text_new": "The '''Kaliwa Low Dam''', proposed by the Philippine Government in 2012, was one of several [[Proposed Dams in the Kaliwa River watershed|bulk water supply projects]] on the upper portion of the Kaliwa River Watershed which have been proposed but ultimately shelved by the [[Philippine Government]] since the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/2177009/china-duterte-and-philippine-dam-set-become-reality-despite|title=China will make Philippines dam a reality, after four decades of protest|date=2018-12-09|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>  \n\nThe proposed Kaliwa Low Dam design had a 600 million-liters-a-day (MLD) capacity, and the water supply tunnel has a 2,400-MLD capacity.   Had it been built, the Kaliwa Low Dam was expected to ease the demand on the [[Angat Dam]], Manila\u2019s sole water storage facility.<ref>{{cite web | last = Smith | first = Sandy  | title = New Starts: Closing 6 Blocks in D.C., Planning K.C. Streetcars From Afar, Manila's New Water Supply | work = nextcity.org | publisher = [[Next City]] | date = June 23, 2014 | url = http://nextcity.org/daily/entry/street-closure-dc-virginia-ave-kansas-city-streetcars-manila-water | doi = | accessdate = June 30, 2014 }}</ref> It was the main component of the New Centennial Water Source-Kaliwa Dam Project in [[Tanay, Rizal]], which also called for the construction of a water supply tunnel and various attendant infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/2177009/china-duterte-and-philippine-dam-set-become-reality-despite|title=China will make Philippines dam a reality, after four decades of protest|date=2018-12-09|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>  \n\nThe project had originally been proposed as a bigger, integrated system which included a plan for a second dam, named [[Laiban dam]] further upstream.  But the government decided on a proposal which would have built the system in stages, and only stage one, involving Kaliwa Low Dam and the water supply tunnel, were approved under the administration of [[Benigno Aquino III]].<ref name=\"Interaksyon20140611\">{{Citation | last = A\u00f1onuevo | first = Euan Paulo C.  | title =Laiban Dam Project next on MWSS' PPP list | publisher = InterAksyon.com | date =June 11, 2014  | url = }}</ref>  When the project did not move forward by the time Aquino administration ended, the succeeding Duterte administration decided not to pursue the Japanese-proposed Kaliwa Low Dam plan and instead pursued a bigger, China-funded dam project.<ref name=\"JairusBondocJapanSafe\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/opinion/2019/04/01/1906196/why-borrow-china-japanese-dam-free-safe |title=Why borrow from China? Japanese dam is free, safe |access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\n== Earlier Projects at the Laiban Watershed ==\nVarious plans for the construction of a dam in Tanay, Rizal, have been proposed since the 1970s, when the Marcos government first decided that the location was a more viable location for a dam than the [[Marikina River]]. However, protests against the construction of the dam, called Laiban because Barangay Laiban was chosen as the exact project site, very quickly led to protests from various groups. Foremost among these were indigenous peoples from Central and Southern Luzon, notably the local Remontado Dumagat people, whose ancestral lands would specifically be affected.<ref name=\"DumagatInquirer20130712\">{{cite news | last = Mallari | first = Delfin T., Jr. | title = Sierra Madre tribe asks Congress to stop Laiban dam | newspaper = [[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | location = Makati City | pages = | language = | publisher = Philippine Daily Inquirer, Inc. | date = July 12, 2013 | url = http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/443527/sierra-madre-tribe-asks-congress-to-stop-laiban-dam | accessdate = July 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer130505\">{{Cite web | url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/402375/tribes-oppose-dams-for-mm-folks-water |title = Tribes oppose dams for MM folk's water &#124; Inquirer News}}</ref> Environmental and activist groups later also raised concerns. As a result, construction of the dam has been approved, deferred, stopped, and restarted a number of times in the decades since.<ref name=\"PCIJChronology\">{{cite web| title =Laiban Dam Project Chronology of Events| work =pcij.org| publisher =Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism| date =July 2009| url =http://pcij.org/resources/laiban-02-chronology.pdf| accessdate =July 1, 2014| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130820192441/http://pcij.org/resources/laiban-02-chronology.pdf| archivedate =2013-08-20| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\n==Project approval process==\n\n=== Original Proposal, including Laiban Dam and Power Plant ===\nThe roots of the current \"New Centennial Water Source Project\" can be traced to the Water Security Legacy (WSL) Roadmap proposed by the [[Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System]] (MWSS) in 2012-2016.  Based on this document, the MWSS developed plans for \"''the development of a dam at the Kaliwa River (Laiban Dam), and/or a smaller dam downstream (Kaliwa Low Dam) to maximize water supply, ensure short - and long - term redundancy, and optimize power generation capacities'',\" and in February 2013, the Public Private Partnership Center released a document \"sounding out\" interested parties.<ref name=\"PPPMarketSounding\">{{Citation | last = | first = | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title =Market Sounding for the New Centennial Water Source Project (NCWP) | publisher = Public-Private Partnership Center | date = February 2013 | url = http://ppp.gov.ph/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/NCWS_MarketSounding.pdf | accessdate = January 30, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn that initial market sounding, this proposal was already thought likely to comprise:<ref name=\"PPPMarketSounding\"/>\n#) Laiban Dam and/or Kaliwa Low Dam; \n#) Head works and its appurtenant facilities; \n#) Conveyance structure from the diversion point to the water treatment facility(s); \n#) Water treatment facility(s); and\n#) Hydropower facility(s).\n\nIn report by Philippine Daily Inquirer reporter Ni\u00f1a Calleja in that same month, MWSS senior deputy administrator Nathaniel Santos indicated that the main difference of the NCWSP from previous plans was that it would involve the construction of two smaller dams at the Kaliwa watershed instead of just the one. A main dam (Laiban Dam) would be built at the upper Kaliwa River in Barangay Laiban, and another regulating dam (Kaliwa Low Dam) further downstream.<ref name=\"DifferentDamCalleja\">{{cite journal | last = Calleja | first = Ni\u00f1a  | authorlink = Ni\u00f1a Calleja | title = P85B MWSS project: Same river in Tanay but different plan: Gov't to undertake project to head off possible water shortage in NCR | journal = [[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | publisher = Philippine Daily Inquirer, Inc. | location = Makati | date = February 25, 2013 | language = | url = http://business.inquirer.net/109277/p85b-mwss-project-same-river-in-tanay-but-different-plan | issn = | accessdate = July 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[National Economic and Development Authority]] (NEDA) Investment Coordination Committee (ICC) had their October 4, 2013 Joint Cabinet Committee and Technical Board Meeting, however, they suggested that the MWSS to develop the project in stages, allowing for construction on the Kaliwa Low Dam to begin sooner, and for the Laiban Dam components of the project to be funded under a different financial mechanism.<ref name=\"Interaksyon20140611\"/><ref name=\"MWSS201307\">{{Citation| title =New Centennial Water Supply Source Project, For Policy Decision by NEDA ICC Cabinet Committee| publisher =[[Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System]]| date =December 3, 2013| url =http://50.57.171.177/r3d3s1gn/2013/07/new-centennial-water-supply-source-project/| accessdate =June 30, 2014| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140528172734/http://50.57.171.177/r3d3s1gn/2013/07/new-centennial-water-supply-source-project/| archivedate =May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Project financing ===\nThe original integrated project had been proposed by the MWSS under a [[Build-Operate-Transfer]] (BOT) financing scheme.  When the Joint Cabinet Committee and Technical Board Meeting of the [[National Economic and Development Authority]] (NEDA) Investment Coordination Committee (ICC) discussed the project on 4 October 2013, however, they recommended that the MWSS resubmit its proposal with only the Kaliwa Low Dam and water supply tunnel components, and that it be funded using the MWSS' funds or though overseas development assistance.<ref name=\"MWSS201307\"/>\n\n=== Approval of Kaliwa Low Dam proposal ===\nThe project, with its revised scope, was approved at the May 29, 2014 meeting of the NEDA Board, which is chaired by President [[Benigno Aquino III]].<ref>http://www.solarnews.ph/news/2014/05/30/neda-approves-nine-projects-worth-p62-billion</ref>\n\nOn July 28, 2014, [[Benigno Simeon Aquino III|President Aquino]] cited Kaliwa dam in his [[Presidency of Benigno Aquino III#Aquino's speeches|5th State of the Nation Address]] as one of the infrastructure projects approved by his administration as part of its drought prevention efforts.<ref name=\"SONAFactCheckRappler\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/special-coverage/sona/2014/64806-sona-2014-fact-check-dike-dam-environmental-threats | title=SONA Fact Check: Dike, dam pose environmental threats}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, two consortia were pre-qualified to bid for the undertaking of the Kaliwa Dam project<ref>https://www.bworldonline.com/integrated-ppp-vs-hybrid-ppp-the-case-of-kaliwa-dam/</ref> \u2014 the SMC-K Water Consortium, which is a partnership between San Miguel Holdings Corp. and Korea Water Resources Corp.; and the Abeima-Datem Consortium, which is a partnership between Albeinsa Infraestructura Medio Ambiento S.A and Datem Inc.<ref>https://www.bworldonline.com/integrated-ppp-vs-hybrid-ppp-the-case-of-kaliwa-dam/</ref>\n\n=== Government shift to Chinese proposal===\nIn 2019, under the [[Presidency of Rodrigo Duterte|administration]] of President [[Rodrigo Duterte]], the government revealed that it would not continue with the project under a [[public\u2013private partnership]] agreement as proposed during the Aquino administration, but would instead pursue the project using [[Official Development Assistance]] loan from China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/3/18/China-Kaliwa-Dam-water-supply1.html|title=Gov't targets construction of China-funded Kaliwa Dam by July|date=March 18, 2019|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nSome lawyers have also noted that the interest rate of the Chinese deal was 2%, while the Japanese deal that was sidelined by the government only had a 1.25% interest.<ref name=\"autogenerated12\">{{Cite web | url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/03/25/diokno-questions-several-provisions-in-p12-2-b-load-agreement-for-kaliwa-dam-project/ |title = Diokno questions several provisions in P12.2-B loan agreement for Kaliwa Dam project}}</ref> The Japanese has since renewed their call for the Philippine government to reconsider their proposal.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1064848 | title=Japanese firm renews proposal on Kaliwa Dam project}}</ref><ref name=\"EMBSummary\">{{Cite web |url=https://emb.gov.ph/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Kaliwa-Dam_Executive-Summary.pdf |website=Environmental Management Bureau}}</ref>\n\n== Social and environmental concerns ==\n\n=== Social issues ===\nAncestral lands belonging to indigenous Dumagats and Remontados will be affected by the Kaliwa Dam project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/03/20/weirs-instead-of-dams-for-our-water-problem|title=Weirs, instead of dams, for our water problem|date=March 20, 2019|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref> The coalition Sectors Opposed to the Kaliwa Dam (STOP Kaliwa Dam) estimate that 1,000 households from Barangay Daraitan in Tanay, Rizal, and 500 households in Pagsangahan, General Nakar, Quezon, will be inundated by the construction.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2019/04/02/1906682/coalition-rejects-china-funded-kaliwa-dam-project|title=Coalition rejects China-funded Kaliwa Dam project|date=April 2, 2019|website=Philstar|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref> The Samahan ng mga Katutubong Agta/Dumagat (Organization of Indigenous Agta/Dumagat) estimate that the project would displace 10,000 members of the Dumagat tribe.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/3/21/agta-dumagat-leader-laments-alleged-lack-of-proper-consent-for-kaliwa-dam-construction.html|title=Dumagat leader laments alleged lack of tribe consent for Kaliwa dam: 'Binabraso nila kami'|last=Vergara|first=Robert|date=March 21, 2019|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> Protesters have maintained that indigenous communities that will be affected by the project were not consulted.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opinion.inquirer.net/120818/the-big-sacrifice|title=The big sacrifice|date=April 17, 2019|website=Philippine Daily Inquirer|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/thought-leaders/235696-analysis-poor-quality-economic-growth-under-duterte|title=[ANALYSIS] The poor quality of economic growth under Duterte|last=Punongbayan|first=J. C.|date=July 18, 2019|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> Philippine law requires that such projects acquire free, prior, and informed consent (FPIC) from indigenous communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1105506/kaliwa-dam-opponets-cite-lack-of-indigenous-peoples-consent|title=Kaliwa Dam opponets cite lack of indigenous people's consent|last=Ramos|first=Mariejo S.|date=April 11, 2019|website=Inquirer|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Environmental issues ===\nSierra Madre is one of the most biodiverse areas in the Philippines and the largest remaining rainforest in the country.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/science-and-environment/2018/11/29/1872521/kaliwa-dam-will-destroy-sierra-madre-biodiversity|title=Kaliwa Dam will destroy Sierra Madre biodiversity|date=November 29, 2018|website=Philstar|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref> An estimated 12,147 hectares of residual forests, home to 172 recorded plant or flora species will be affected by the dam construction.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe project site is part of the Kaliwa Watershed Forest Reserve, which is supposedly protected by virtue of Proclamation No. 573 on June 22, 1968.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2019/03/14/145764/why-china-funded-kaliwa-dam-a-possible-alternate-water-source-is-heavily-opposed/|title=Why China-funded Kaliwa Dam, a possible alternate water source, is heavily opposed|last=Madarang|first=Catalina Ricci S.|date=2019-03-14|website=Interaksyon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref> Proclamation 1636 declared a portion of the area a National Park and Wildlife Sanctuary.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEnvironmental groups have protested the project, as the dam will destroy a great portion of the Sierra Madre range. The dam will ultimately destroy numerous habitats of many [[endangered species]] living in the mountains, once construction begins.<ref name=\"youtube1\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3otb60P_2eg</ref> Among the thousands of plant and animal life whose home will be destroyed by the project is the critically endangered [[Philippine eagle]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Other species that will be affected by the project are the endangered [[Philippine hawk-eagle|north Philippine hawk-eagle]], the [[Philippine deer|Philippine brown deer]], the [[Philippine warty pig]], and the vulnerable [[Rufous hornbill|northern rufous hornbill]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Proposed Dams in the Kaliwa River watershed]]\n*[[Manila Water Supply III project]]\n*[[Angat Dam]]\n*[[Wawa Dam]]\n*[[Chico River Dam Project]]\n*[[Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n[[Category:Dams in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Sierra Madre (Philippines)]]\n[[Category:Proposed water supply infrastructure]]\n[[Category:Cancelled dams]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Kaliwa Low Dam''', proposed by the Philippine Government in 2012, was one of several [[Proposed Dams in the Kaliwa River watershed|bulk water supply projects]] on the upper portion of the Kaliwa River Watershed which have been proposed but ultimately shelved by the [[Philippine Government]] since the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/2177009/china-duterte-and-philippine-dam-set-become-reality-despite|title=China will make Philippines dam a reality, after four decades of protest|date=2018-12-09|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>  \n\nThe proposed Kaliwa Low Dam design had a 600 million-liters-a-day (MLD) capacity, and the water supply tunnel has a 2,400-MLD capacity.   Had it been built, the Kaliwa Low Dam was expected to ease the demand on the [[Angat Dam]], Manila\u2019s sole water storage facility.<ref>{{cite web | last = Smith | first = Sandy  | title = New Starts: Closing 6 Blocks in D.C., Planning K.C. Streetcars From Afar, Manila's New Water Supply | work = nextcity.org | publisher = [[Next City]] | date = June 23, 2014 | url = http://nextcity.org/daily/entry/street-closure-dc-virginia-ave-kansas-city-streetcars-manila-water | doi = | accessdate = June 30, 2014 }}</ref> It was the main component of the New Centennial Water Source-Kaliwa Dam Project in [[Tanay, Rizal]], which also called for the construction of a water supply tunnel and various attendant infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/2177009/china-duterte-and-philippine-dam-set-become-reality-despite|title=China will make Philippines dam a reality, after four decades of protest|date=2018-12-09|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>  \n\nThe project had originally been proposed as a bigger, integrated system which included a plan for a second dam, named [[Laiban dam]] further upstream.  But the government decided on a proposal which would have built the system in stages, and only stage one, involving Kaliwa Low Dam and the water supply tunnel, were approved under the administration of [[Benigno Aquino III]].<ref name=\"Interaksyon20140611\">{{Citation | last = A\u00f1onuevo | first = Euan Paulo C.  | title =Laiban Dam Project next on MWSS' PPP list | publisher = InterAksyon.com | date =June 11, 2014  | url = }}</ref>  When the project did not move forward by the time Aquino administration ended, the succeeding Duterte administration decided not to pursue the Japanese-proposed Kaliwa Low Dam plan and instead pursued a bigger, China-funded dam project.<ref name=\"JairusBondocJapanSafe\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/opinion/2019/04/01/1906196/why-borrow-china-japanese-dam-free-safe |title=Why borrow from China? Japanese dam is free, safe |access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\n== Earlier Projects at the Laiban Watershed ==\nVarious plans for the construction of a dam in Tanay, Rizal, have been proposed since the 1970s, when the Marcos government first decided that the location was a more viable location for a dam than the [[Marikina River]]. However, protests against the construction of the dam, called Laiban because Barangay Laiban was chosen as the exact project site, very quickly led to protests from various groups. Foremost among these were indigenous peoples from Central and Southern Luzon, notably the local Remontado Dumagat people, whose ancestral lands would specifically be affected.<ref name=\"DumagatInquirer20130712\">{{cite news | last = Mallari | first = Delfin T., Jr. | title = Sierra Madre tribe asks Congress to stop Laiban dam | newspaper = [[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | location = Makati City | pages = | language = | publisher = Philippine Daily Inquirer, Inc. | date = July 12, 2013 | url = http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/443527/sierra-madre-tribe-asks-congress-to-stop-laiban-dam | accessdate = July 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer130505\">{{Cite web | url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/402375/tribes-oppose-dams-for-mm-folks-water |title = Tribes oppose dams for MM folk's water &#124; Inquirer News}}</ref> Environmental and activist groups later also raised concerns. As a result, construction of the dam has been approved, deferred, stopped, and restarted a number of times in the decades since.<ref name=\"PCIJChronology\">{{cite web| title =Laiban Dam Project Chronology of Events| work =pcij.org| publisher =Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism| date =July 2009| url =http://pcij.org/resources/laiban-02-chronology.pdf| accessdate =July 1, 2014| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130820192441/http://pcij.org/resources/laiban-02-chronology.pdf| archivedate =2013-08-20| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\n==Project approval process==\n\n=== Original Proposal, including Laiban Dam and Power Plant ===\nThe roots of the current \"New Centennial Water Source Project\" can be traced to the Water Security Legacy (WSL) Roadmap proposed by the [[Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System]] (MWSS) in 2012-2016.  Based on this document, the MWSS developed plans for \"''the development of a dam at the Kaliwa River (Laiban Dam), and/or a smaller dam downstream (Kaliwa Low Dam) to maximize water supply, ensure short - and long - term redundancy, and optimize power generation capacities'',\" and in February 2013, the Public Private Partnership Center released a document \"sounding out\" interested parties.<ref name=\"PPPMarketSounding\">{{Citation | last = | first = | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title =Market Sounding for the New Centennial Water Source Project (NCWP) | publisher = Public-Private Partnership Center | date = February 2013 | url = http://ppp.gov.ph/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/NCWS_MarketSounding.pdf | accessdate = January 30, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn that initial market sounding, this proposal was already thought likely to comprise:<ref name=\"PPPMarketSounding\"/>\n#) Laiban Dam and/or Kaliwa Low Dam; \n#) Head works and its appurtenant facilities; \n#) Conveyance structure from the diversion point to the water treatment facility(s); \n#) Water treatment facility(s); and\n#) Hydropower facility(s).\n\nIn report by Philippine Daily Inquirer reporter Ni\u00f1a Calleja in that same month, MWSS senior deputy administrator Nathaniel Santos indicated that the main difference of the NCWSP from previous plans was that it would involve the construction of two smaller dams at the Kaliwa watershed instead of just the one. A main dam (Laiban Dam) would be built at the upper Kaliwa River in Barangay Laiban, and another regulating dam (Kaliwa Low Dam) further downstream.<ref name=\"DifferentDamCalleja\">{{cite journal | last = Calleja | first = Ni\u00f1a  | authorlink = Ni\u00f1a Calleja | title = P85B MWSS project: Same river in Tanay but different plan: Gov't to undertake project to head off possible water shortage in NCR | journal = [[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | publisher = Philippine Daily Inquirer, Inc. | location = Makati | date = February 25, 2013 | language = | url = http://business.inquirer.net/109277/p85b-mwss-project-same-river-in-tanay-but-different-plan | issn = | accessdate = July 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[National Economic and Development Authority]] (NEDA) Investment Coordination Committee (ICC) had their October 4, 2013 Joint Cabinet Committee and Technical Board Meeting, however, they suggested that the MWSS to develop the project in stages, allowing for construction on the Kaliwa Low Dam to begin sooner, and for the Laiban Dam components of the project to be funded under a different financial mechanism.<ref name=\"Interaksyon20140611\"/><ref name=\"MWSS201307\">{{Citation| title =New Centennial Water Supply Source Project, For Policy Decision by NEDA ICC Cabinet Committee| publisher =[[Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System]]| date =December 3, 2013| url =http://50.57.171.177/r3d3s1gn/2013/07/new-centennial-water-supply-source-project/| accessdate =June 30, 2014| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140528172734/http://50.57.171.177/r3d3s1gn/2013/07/new-centennial-water-supply-source-project/| archivedate =May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Project financing ===\nThe original integrated project had been proposed by the MWSS under a [[Build-Operate-Transfer]] (BOT) financing scheme.  When the Joint Cabinet Committee and Technical Board Meeting of the [[National Economic and Development Authority]] (NEDA) Investment Coordination Committee (ICC) discussed the project on 4 October 2013, however, they recommended that the MWSS resubmit its proposal with only the Kaliwa Low Dam and water supply tunnel components, and that it be funded using the MWSS' funds or though overseas development assistance.<ref name=\"MWSS201307\"/>\n\n=== Approval of Kaliwa Low Dam proposal ===\nThe project, with its revised scope, was approved at the May 29, 2014 meeting of the NEDA Board, which is chaired by President [[Benigno Aquino III]].<ref>http://www.solarnews.ph/news/2014/05/30/neda-approves-nine-projects-worth-p62-billion</ref>\n\nOn July 28, 2014, [[Benigno Simeon Aquino III|President Aquino]] cited Kaliwa dam in his [[Presidency of Benigno Aquino III#Aquino's speeches|5th State of the Nation Address]] as one of the infrastructure projects approved by his administration as part of its drought prevention efforts.<ref name=\"SONAFactCheckRappler\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/special-coverage/sona/2014/64806-sona-2014-fact-check-dike-dam-environmental-threats | title=SONA Fact Check: Dike, dam pose environmental threats}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, two consortia were pre-qualified to bid for the undertaking of the Kaliwa Dam project<ref>https://www.bworldonline.com/integrated-ppp-vs-hybrid-ppp-the-case-of-kaliwa-dam/</ref> \u2014 the SMC-K Water Consortium, which is a partnership between San Miguel Holdings Corp. and Korea Water Resources Corp.; and the Abeima-Datem Consortium, which is a partnership between Albeinsa Infraestructura Medio Ambiento S.A and Datem Inc.<ref>https://www.bworldonline.com/integrated-ppp-vs-hybrid-ppp-the-case-of-kaliwa-dam/</ref>\n\n=== Government shift to Chinese proposal===\nIn 2019, under the [[Presidency of Rodrigo Duterte|administration]] of President [[Rodrigo Duterte]], the government revealed that it would not continue with the project under a [[public\u2013private partnership]] agreement as proposed during the Aquino administration, but would instead pursue the project using [[Official Development Assistance]] loan from China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/3/18/China-Kaliwa-Dam-water-supply1.html|title=Gov't targets construction of China-funded Kaliwa Dam by July|date=March 18, 2019|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nSome lawyers have also noted that the interest rate of the Chinese deal was 2%, while the Japanese deal that was sidelined by the government only had a 1.25% interest.<ref name=\"autogenerated12\">{{Cite web | url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/03/25/diokno-questions-several-provisions-in-p12-2-b-load-agreement-for-kaliwa-dam-project/ |title = Diokno questions several provisions in P12.2-B loan agreement for Kaliwa Dam project}}</ref> The Japanese has since renewed their call for the Philippine government to reconsider their proposal.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1064848 | title=Japanese firm renews proposal on Kaliwa Dam project}}</ref><ref name=\"EMBSummary\">{{Cite web |url=https://emb.gov.ph/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Kaliwa-Dam_Executive-Summary.pdf |website=Environmental Management Bureau}}</ref>\n\n== Social and environmental concerns ==\n\n=== Social issues ===\nAncestral lands belonging to indigenous Dumagats and Remontados will be affected by the Kaliwa Dam project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/03/20/weirs-instead-of-dams-for-our-water-problem|title=Weirs, instead of dams, for our water problem|date=March 20, 2019|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref> The coalition Sectors Opposed to the Kaliwa Dam (STOP Kaliwa Dam) estimate that 1,000 households from Barangay Daraitan in Tanay, Rizal, and 500 households in Pagsangahan, General Nakar, Quezon, will be inundated by the construction.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2019/04/02/1906682/coalition-rejects-china-funded-kaliwa-dam-project|title=Coalition rejects China-funded Kaliwa Dam project|date=April 2, 2019|website=Philstar|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref> The Samahan ng mga Katutubong Agta/Dumagat (Organization of Indigenous Agta/Dumagat) estimate that the project would displace 10,000 members of the Dumagat tribe.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/3/21/agta-dumagat-leader-laments-alleged-lack-of-proper-consent-for-kaliwa-dam-construction.html|title=Dumagat leader laments alleged lack of tribe consent for Kaliwa dam: 'Binabraso nila kami'|last=Vergara|first=Robert|date=March 21, 2019|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> Protesters have maintained that indigenous communities that will be affected by the project were not consulted.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opinion.inquirer.net/120818/the-big-sacrifice|title=The big sacrifice|date=April 17, 2019|website=Philippine Daily Inquirer|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/thought-leaders/235696-analysis-poor-quality-economic-growth-under-duterte|title=[ANALYSIS] The poor quality of economic growth under Duterte|last=Punongbayan|first=J. C.|date=July 18, 2019|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> Philippine law requires that such projects acquire free, prior, and informed consent (FPIC) from indigenous communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1105506/kaliwa-dam-opponets-cite-lack-of-indigenous-peoples-consent|title=Kaliwa Dam opponets cite lack of indigenous people's consent|last=Ramos|first=Mariejo S.|date=April 11, 2019|website=Inquirer|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Environmental issues ===\nSierra Madre is one of the most biodiverse areas in the Philippines and the largest remaining rainforest in the country.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/science-and-environment/2018/11/29/1872521/kaliwa-dam-will-destroy-sierra-madre-biodiversity|title=Kaliwa Dam will destroy Sierra Madre biodiversity|date=November 29, 2018|website=Philstar|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref> An estimated 12,147 hectares of residual forests, home to 172 recorded plant or flora species will be affected by the dam construction.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe project site is part of the Kaliwa Watershed Forest Reserve, which is supposedly protected by virtue of Proclamation No. 573 on June 22, 1968.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2019/03/14/145764/why-china-funded-kaliwa-dam-a-possible-alternate-water-source-is-heavily-opposed/|title=Why China-funded Kaliwa Dam, a possible alternate water source, is heavily opposed|last=Madarang|first=Catalina Ricci S.|date=2019-03-14|website=Interaksyon|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref> Proclamation 1636 declared a portion of the area a National Park and Wildlife Sanctuary.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEnvironmental groups have protested the project, as the dam will destroy a great portion of the Sierra Madre range. The dam will ultimately destroy numerous habitats of many [[endangered species]] living in the mountains, once construction begins.<ref name=\"youtube1\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3otb60P_2eg</ref> Among the thousands of plant and animal life whose home will be destroyed by the project is the critically endangered [[Philippine eagle]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Other species that will be affected by the project are the endangered [[Philippine hawk-eagle|north Philippine hawk-eagle]], the [[Philippine deer|Philippine brown deer]], the [[Philippine warty pig]], and the vulnerable [[Rufous hornbill|northern rufous hornbill]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Proposed Dams in the Kaliwa River watershed]]\n*[[Manila Water Supply III project]]\n*[[Angat Dam]]\n*[[Wawa Dam]]\n*[[Chico River Dam Project]]\n*[[Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Proposed dams]]\n[[Category:Dams in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Sierra Madre (Philippines)]]\n[[Category:Proposed water supply infrastructure]]\n", "name_user": "Macquaria", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moved from category \"Proposed dams\" to more appropriate \"Cancelled dams\" since\" the project is cancelled", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaliwa_Low_Dam"}
{"title_page": "Geoff Gardner", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n'''Geoffrey Robert Gardner''' (born 1961) is a political figure from the [[Australia|Australian]] territory of [[Norfolk Island]].\n\n==Chief Minister of Norfolk Island==\nGardner was the chief minister of [[Norfolk Island]] from 5 December 2001 to 2 June 2006. He was succeeded in that post by [[David Buffett]].\n\n==Speaker of the Legislative Assembly==\nGardner was appointed Speaker of the [[Norfolk Legislative Assembly]] in 2006, serving until 2007.\n==Athletics==\nGardner is the vice-president of the-[ World Athletics - formerly the International,Association of Athletics Federations]] and up until September 2019 was the president of [[Oceania Athletics Association|Oceania Athletics]] since 2007.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Norfolk Island]]\n\n==Link==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20080719102547/http://www.norfolk.gov.nf/geoff_gardner.htm\n\n{{NorfolkIsPMs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardner, Geoffrey Robert}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Heads of government of Norfolk Island]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{NorfolkIsland-politician-stub}}\n{{Australia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n'''Geoffrey Robert Gardner''' (born 1961) is a political figure from the [[Australia|Australian]] territory of [[Norfolk Island]].\n\n==Chief Minister of Norfolk Island==\nGardner was the chief minister of [[Norfolk Island]] from 5 December 2001 to 2 June 2006. He was succeeded in that post by [[David Buffett]].\n\n==Speaker of the Legislative Assembly==\nGardner was appointed Speaker of the [[Norfolk Legislative Assembly]] in 2006, serving until 2007.\n==Athletics==\nGardner is the vice-president of the-[ World Athletics - formerly the International,Association of Athletics Federations]] and up until September of 2019 was the president of [[Oceania Athletics Association|Oceania Athletics]] since 2007.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Norfolk Island]]\n\n==Link==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20080719102547/http://www.norfolk.gov.nf/geoff_gardner.htm\n\n{{NorfolkIsPMs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardner, Geoffrey Robert}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Heads of government of Norfolk Island]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{NorfolkIsland-politician-stub}}\n{{Australia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAthletics:clean up,typo(s) fixed: September of 2019 \u2192 September 2019", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geoff_Gardner"}
{"title_page": "Albert Riera", "text_new": "{{about|the former Spain international footballer|another Spanish footballer|Albert Riera (footballer, born 1983)}}\n{{Spanish name|Riera|Ortega}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Albert Riera\n| image = 1 albert riera 2017.jpg\n| caption = Riera playing a friendly with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2017\n| fullname = Albert Riera Ortega<ref>{{cite web|url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=26921|title=Acta del partido celebrado el 10 de mayo de 2015, en Palma de Mallorca|trans-title=Minutes of the match held on 10 May 2015, in Palma de Mallorca|publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]]|language=Spanish|date=10 May 2015|accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|4|15|df=y}}<ref name=Profile>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/envivos/fichas/1/166/4262.html|title=Albert RIERA Ortega|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Manacor]], Spain<ref name=Profile/>\n| height = 1.87 m<ref name=Profile/>\n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]], [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]]\n| currentclub =\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1999\u20132000 | youthclubs1 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n| years1 = 2000\u20132002 | clubs1 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] | caps1 = 54 | goals1 = 12\n| years2 = 2001\u20132003 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps2 = 46 | goals2 = 6\n| years3 = 2003\u20132005 | clubs3 = [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] | caps3 = 53 | goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2005\u20132008 | clubs4 = [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] | caps4 = 72 | goals4 = 8\n| years5 = 2006 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] (loan) | caps5 = 15 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2008\u20132010 | clubs6 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] | caps6 = 40 | goals6 = 3\n| years7 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs7 = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] | caps7 = 26 | goals7 = 6\n| years8 = 2011\u20132014 | clubs8 = [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] | caps8 = 60 | goals8 = 3\n| years9 = 2014 | clubs9 = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] | caps9 = 8 | goals9 = 1\n| years10 = 2014 | clubs10 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] | caps10 = 0 | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2015 | clubs11 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps11 = 6 | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 2015 | clubs12 = [[NK Zavr\u010d|Zavr\u010d]] | caps12 = 12 | goals12 = 1\n| years13 = 2016 | clubs13 = [[FC Koper|Koper]] | caps13 = 1 | goals13 = 0\n| totalcaps = 393 | totalgoals = 45\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\u20132001 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 11 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2002\u20132003 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps2 = 15 | nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2007\u20132009 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps3 = 16 | nationalgoals3 = 4\n}}\n'''Albert Riera Ortega''' (born 15 April 1982) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played mainly as a [[Midfielder#Winger|left winger]] but also as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]].\n\nHe made a name for himself at [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] (where he won one [[Copa del Rey]] and reached one [[2007 UEFA Cup Final|UEFA Cup final]]) and also played professionally in France, England, Greece, Turkey, Italy and Slovenia, notably spending three years with [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]].\n\nRiera won 16 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Spain national football team|Spain]], representing the nation at the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009 Confederations Cup]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Mallorca===\nBorn in [[Manacor]], [[Balearic Islands]], Riera started his professional career with hometown club [[RCD Mallorca]], but could only make a combined ten [[La Liga]] appearances in his first two seasons.\n\nIn the [[2002\u201303 La Liga|2002\u201303 campaign]], already an undisputed starter, he helped the local team to [[2002\u201303 Copa del Rey|the conquest]] of the [[Copa del Rey]],<ref name=COPA>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/06/29/deportes/1056837603_850215.html|title=Eto'o pone Mallorca a brindar|trans-title=Eto'o has Mallorca toasting|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|first=Jos\u00e9|last=Miguelez|language=Spanish|date=29 June 2003|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> and scored four league goals in 35 games.<ref name=Mirror>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/most-popular/2008/08/29/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-new-liverpool-signing-albert-riera-115875-20716276/|title=10 things you need to know about new Liverpool signing Albert Riera|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|first=Dan|last=Silver|date=29 August 2008|accessdate=1 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614145034/http://www.mirror.co.uk/most-popular/2008/08/29/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-new-liverpool-signing-albert-riera-115875-20716276/|archivedate=14 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Bordeaux===\nIn the summer of 2003, Riera moved to [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=86920.html|title=Riera raring to go at Bordeaux|publisher=UEFA|date=31 July 2003|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref> where he was a first-team regular for two years.\n\nHe made 66 competitive appearances for the [[Ligue 1]] side, and netted nine times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football365.fr/espagnols-de-ligue-1-diapo-2653871.html#item=1|title=Les espagnols de la Ligue 1 [Diapo]|trans-title=The Ligue 1 Spaniards [Diapo]|publisher=Football 365|language=French|date=8 August 2016|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Espanyol===\nRiera returned to Spain in 2005, when he signed for [[RCD Espanyol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=315451.html|title=Riera wings into Espanyol|publisher=UEFA|date=7 July 2005|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref> In [[2005\u201306 La Liga|his first season]] he played only eight league matches, prompting a January 2006 loan move to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=382387.html|title=City tempt Riera to England|publisher=UEFA|date=5 January 2006|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref> where he was also unable to establish himself, scoring against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in a 3\u20130 home win on 1 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4657216.stm|title=Man City 3\u20130 Newcastle|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=1 February 2006|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nRiera returned to [[Catalonia]] prior to [[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]]. During that season, Espanyol [[2006\u201307 UEFA Cup|reached]] [[2007 UEFA Cup Final|the final]] of the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] at [[Hampden Park]], Glasgow, where they played fellow Spaniards [[Sevilla FC]]: he scored to level the game at 1\u20131, but his team eventually lost 1\u20133 on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]].<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6657065.stm|title=Espanyol 2\u20132 Sevilla|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Charlie|last=Henderson|date=16 May 2007|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> At the end of the campaign, he extended his contract until 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2007/08/23/mas_futbol/1187820012_850215.html|title=Riera prolonga su contrato con el Espanyol hasta el 2011|trans-title=Riera extends his contract with Espanyol until 2011|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|language=Spanish|date=23 August 2007|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Liverpool===\n[[File:2009-3-14 ManUtd vs LFC Ronaldo Tackling cropped.JPG|thumb|upright|Riera (left) in action for Liverpool.]]\nOn 1 September 2008 (transfer deadline day), Riera signed a four-year deal with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] for a fee of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]8 million, being given the number 11 shirt.<ref name=Mirror/> He made his [[Premier League]] debut on the 13th, playing 71 minutes of a 2\u20131 home win against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/7601885.stm|title=Liverpool 2\u20131 Man Utd|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Mandeep|last=Sanghera|date=13 September 2008|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref> and scored his first goal for the Reds as they beat [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] 3\u20132 on 18 October,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7665090.stm|title=Liverpool 3\u20132 Wigan|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Russell|last=Barder|date=18 October 2008|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> adding another in [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|the group stage]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]] in a 3\u20131 victory at [[PSV Eindhoven]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7763223.stm|title=PSV 1\u20133 Liverpool|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Ian|last=Hughes|date=9 December 2008|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nRiera netted Liverpool's first goal of 2009, and also scored in [[2008\u201309 FA Cup|the third round]] in the [[FA Cup]] on 3 January, against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/7803324.stm|title=Preston 0\u20132 Liverpool|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Mark|last=Ashenden|date=3 January 2009|accessdate=22 September 2009}}</ref> Later during [[2008\u201309 Premier League|that season]] he scored against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in a 5\u20130 home rout on 22 March 2009, through a half-volley after [[Pepe Reina]]'s long [[goal kick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7937107.stm|title=Liverpool 5\u20130 Aston Villa|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Phil|last=McNulty|date=22 March 2009|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2010, Riera was suspended after comments made to the Spanish press regarding his first team opportunities and the approach of Liverpool manager [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]]. The player was quoted as saying: \"He's never sorted out a situation with a player by talking with him.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8574001.stm|title=Rafael Benitez keen to offload outspoken Albert Riera|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 March 2010|accessdate=28 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325093806/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8574001.stm|archivedate=25 March 2010}}</ref> He was transfer listed following the comments, with Russian clubs [[PFC CSKA Moscow]] and [[FC Spartak Moscow]] thought to be interested in a permanent move.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rafael-benitez-banishes-vocal-albert-riera-vn7h67wkg7r|title=Rafael Benitez banishes vocal Albert Riera|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=19 March 2010|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> On the 23rd of that month it was announced that Liverpool had accepted a \u00a36 million bid from CSKA for the player;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/mar/23/albert-riera-rafael-benitez-liverpool-transfer|title=Liverpool accept \u00a36m offer from CSKA Moscow for Albert Riera|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|first=Andy|last=Hunter|date=24 March 2010|accessdate=28 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324193143/http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2010/mar/23/albert-riera-rafael-benitez-liverpool-transfer|archivedate=24 March 2010}}</ref> however, it appeared to be solely rumours, any interest was officially denied<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=761284&sec=transfers&cc=5739|title=CSKA deny interest in Albert Riera|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=28 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402070914/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=761284&sec=transfers&cc=5739|archivedate=2 April 2010}}</ref>\u2013 additionally, the player's agent, \u00c1ngel Castells, confirmed that only Spartak had made a proposal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/Benitez/subasta/Riera/elpepidep/20100327elpepidep_6/Tes|title=Ben\u00edtez 'subasta' a Riera|trans-title=Ben\u00edtez 'auctions' Riera|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|first=Jordi|last=Quixano|language=Spanish|date=27 March 2010|accessdate=28 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Olympiacos===\nOn 23 July 2010, Riera joined Greek club [[Olympiacos F.C.]] on a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8843423.stm|title=Liverpool winger Albert Riera completes Olympiakos move|publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 July 2010|accessdate=23 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723133030/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8843423.stm|archivedate=23 July 2010}}</ref> The deal was reported to be worth around [[Euro|\u20ac]]6 million (\u20ac4 million plus another potential \u20ac2&nbsp;million in bonuses), with a salary of around \u20ac2.5&nbsp;million per season; he became one of the most expensive transfers in the country's history, as he reunited with former Espanyol manager [[Ernesto Valverde]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1549/rest-of-europe/2010/07/23/2039025/breaking-news-official-olympiacos-sign-albert-riera-from|title=Official: Olympiacos sign Albert Riera from Liverpool|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Adam|last=Scime|date=23 July 2010|accessdate=23 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725014848/http://www.goal.com/en/news/1549/rest-of-europe/2010/07/23/2039025/breaking-news-official-olympiacos-sign-albert-riera-from|archivedate=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nRiera scored his first goal for Olympiacos against [[Kerkyra F.C.]] in a 2\u20130 home win, and appeared in more than 30 official games during [[2010\u201311 Superleague Greece|the season]] as the [[Piraeus]] team won the [[Superleague Greece|Superleague]].\n\n===Galatasaray===\n[[File:Riera.JPG|left|thumb|180px|Riera playing for Galatasaray against [[Ankaragucu|Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc]] (2012).]]\nOn 3 September 2011, Riera completed a \u20ac3 million move to Turkish giants [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray SK]], signing a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/es/news/21/fichajes/2011/09/03/2648808/es-oficial-el-galatasaray-ficha-a-albert-riera|title=Es oficial: El Galatasaray ficha a Albert Riera|trans-title=It's official: Galatasaray sign Albert Riera|publisher=Goal|language=Spanish|date=3 September 2011|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goal in the [[S\u00fcper Lig]] on 25 January 2012 in a 4\u20130 home defeat of [[MKE Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc]], and was an habitual first-choice in [[2011\u201312 S\u00fcper Lig|his first season]] as the [[Istanbul]]-based team won the national championship; he was also involved, however, in a punching session with teammate [[Felipe Melo]] just before the playoffs started.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/melo-riera-brawl-overshadows-last-week-in-the-super-league.aspx?pageID=238&nID=17843&NewsCatID=362|title=Melo-Riera brawl overshadows last week in the Super League|newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]]|date=7 April 2012|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the arrival of prospect [[Nordin Amrabat]] for the [[2012\u201313 S\u00fcper Lig|2012\u201313 campaign]], Riera was reconverted by manager [[Fatih Terim]] into an attacking [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]], mainly due to the lack of options in the position other than injury-prone [[Hakan Balta]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/03/29/en/football/real_madrid/1364512402.html|title=\"Galatasaray fans win games\"|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|first=Juan Ignacio|last=Garc\u00eda-Ochoa|date=29 March 2013|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> On 28 January 2014, he agreed to have his contract terminated for \u20ac750,000 and left the [[T\u00fcrk Telekom Stadium|Ali Sami Yen Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccernews.com/riera-amrabat-leave-galatasaray/136985/|title=Riera, Amrabat leave Galatasaray|publisher=Soccer News|first=Nemanja|last=Lazarevic|date=28 January 2014|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nOn 24 March 2014, Riera signed a pre-contract with Italian side [[Udinese Calcio]], effective as of 1 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udinese.it/portal/IT/handle/?hil&page=redazione_approfondimenti&vid=2312|title=Primo tassello per la prossima stagione: ha firmato Albert Riera Ortega|trans-title=First piece for next season: Albert Riera Ortega has signed|publisher=Udinese Calcio|language=Italian|date=24 March 2014|accessdate=24 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324190225/http://www.udinese.it/portal/IT/handle/?hil&page=redazione_approfondimenti&vid=2312|archivedate=24 March 2014}}</ref> Three days later, he joined [[Football League Championship]]'s [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] until the end of [[2013\u201314 Football League Championship|the season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/watford-sign-former-liverpool-and-spain-winger-albert-riera-on-until-the-end-of-season-9219203.html|title=Watford sign former Liverpool and Spain winger Albert Riera on until the end of season|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nRiera scored his first and only goal for Watford on 19 April 2014, in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26998629|title=Watford 3\u20131 Ipswich|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 April 2014|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> He had an extended run until late in the month, when he was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] for two bookable offences in a 1\u20133 loss at [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Chartlton Athletic]] after a high challenge on [[Diego Poyet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140429-charlton-match-report-1518040.aspx|title=Match report: Charlton Athletic 3\u20131 Watford|publisher=Watford F.C|date=29 April 2014|accessdate=18 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617183228/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140429-charlton-match-report-1518040.aspx|archivedate=17 June 2014}}</ref> After the match, he was charged by [[The Football Association]] for improper conduct, having confronted the officials and having to be dragged away by his team-mates;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11686/9291696/watford-winger-albert-riera-faces-fa-misconduct-charge-over-reaction-to-red-card|title=Watford winger Albert Riera faces FA misconduct charge over reaction to red card|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=1 May 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> he was given a two-match ban although only one remained to end the campaign,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/sport/11193325.Riera_handed_additional_one_match_suspension/|title=Watford's Albert Riera handed additional one-match ban by the FA for his conduct following his red card against Charlton Athletic|newspaper=[[Watford Observer]]|date=6 May 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> and he subsequently returned to Udinese.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140604-released-players-announcement-1602043.aspx|title=Official: Released players confirmed|publisher=Watford F.C|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617184821/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140604-released-players-announcement-1602043.aspx|archivedate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 November 2014, Riera was sacked by Udinese for attending a [[poker tournament]] rather than reporting to play against [[A.C. ChievoVerona]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Udinese/24-11-2014/udinese-albert-riera-asso-poker-secondo-un-torneo-mentre-compagni-pareggiano-col-chievo-10040405691.shtml|title=Udinese, Albert Riera, il calciatore dimenticato che vince a poker|trans-title=Udinese, Albert Riera, the forgotten player who wins at poker|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|language=Italian|date=24 November 2014|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2284157-ex-liverpool-man-albert-riera-sacked-by-udinese-after-missing-game-to-play-poker|title=Ex-Liverpool man Albert Riera sacked by Udinese after missing game to play poker|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|first=Mark|last=Patterson|date=30 November 2014|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref> also taking to [[Twitter]] to insult the organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calcioweb.eu/2014/11/udinese-riera-cacciato-via-insultava-la-squadra-su-twitter-e-giocava-poker-durante-le-partite/150706/|title=Udinese \u2013 Riera cacciato via: insultava la squadra su Twitter e giocava a poker durante le partite|trans-title=Udinese \u2013 Riera gets the boot: insulting squad on Twitter and playing poker during match|publisher=Calcio Web|first=Giuseppe|last=Mazza|date=29 November 2014|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref> He returned to his first club Mallorca the following 5 March, after agreeing to a one-and-a-half year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=34094&idmenu=3|title=Riera vuelve a casa|trans-title=Riera returns home|publisher=RCD Mallorca|language=Spanish|date=5 March 2015|accessdate=15 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402190016/http://rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=34094&idmenu=3|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> In May, he was subjected to disciplinary proceedings after claiming he would not appear again for the team as long as [[Miquel Soler]] was the manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2015/05/19/futbol/equipos/mallorca/1432033628.html|title=El Mallorca abre expediente a Riera por \"grave indisciplina\"|trans-title=Mallorca start disciplinary proceedings on Riera for \"severe breach of discipline\"|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=19 May 2015|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 2015, Slovenian sports newspaper [[Ekipa (Slovenia)|''Ekipa'']] reported that Riera would sign a contract with [[NK Zavr\u010d]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ekipa24.si/clanek/nogomet/prva-liga/55f2caaedd306/zavrc-koper-senzacija-prihaja-nekdanji-spanski-reprezentant|title=Zavrc \u2013 Koper: Senzacija! Prihaja nekdanji spanski reprezentant|trans-title=Zavrc \u2013 Koper: Surprise! Former Spanish international arrives|newspaper=[[Ekipa (Slovenia)|Ekipa]]|language=Slovenian|date=11 September 2015|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> Three days later, he was officially presented.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ekipa24.si/clanek/nogomet/prva-liga/55f84490a6d90/ekskluzivno-ce-niste-verjeli-zdaj-morate-riera-na-treningu-v-zavrcu|title=Riera v dresu Zavr\u010da|trans-title=Riera in Zavrc's jersey|newspaper=Ekipa|language=Slovenian|date=15 September 2015|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nRiera terminated his contract on 22 January 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtvslo.si/sport/nogomet/riera-sporazumno-zapusca-zavrc/384016|title=Riera sporazumno zapu\u0161\u010da Zavr\u010d|trans-title=Riera is leaving Zavrc after mutual contract termination|publisher=[[RTV Slovenija]]|author=S.J.|language=Slovenian|date=22 January 2016|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> but remained in the country as he joined [[FC Koper]] until June 2018 shortly after.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nogomania.com/Slovenski-Nogomet/Ekipa/Koper/Novica/Rieri-pogodba-kar-do-leta-2018.aspx|title=Rieri pogodba kar do leta 2018|trans-title=Riera signed until 2018|publisher=Nogomania|author=Uredni\u0161tvo|language=Slovenian|date=26 January 2016|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> He was released in July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://snportal.si/prva-liga/riera-ni-vec-clan-kopra/|title=Riera ni ve\u010d \u010dlan Kopra|trans-title=Riera is no longer a member of Koper|publisher=SN Portal|first=Peter|last=Dominko|language=Slovenian|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nRiera officially announced his retirement from football on 24 January 2018, through a social media post portraying himself having literally hung up his boots on a tree.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/01/24/primera/1516815671_549262.html|title=Albert Riera se retira del f\u00fatbol: \"Es hora de decir adi\u00f3s\"|trans-title=Albert Riera retires from football: \"It's time to say goodbye\"|newspaper=Diario AS|language=Spanish|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nRiera made his debut for the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]] on 13 October 2007 in an [[UEFA Euro 2008]] [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying|qualifier]] against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]], and scored from outside the box in a 3\u20131 away win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/289897/0/victoria/seleccion/dinamarca/|title=Espa\u00f1a sale del t\u00fanel tras su triunfo en Dinamarca (1\u20133)|trans-title=Spain exit tunnel after win in Denmark (1\u20133)|newspaper=[[20 minutos]]|language=Spanish|date=13 October 2007|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=603234.html#espanyol+flag+spain|title=Espanyol fly flag for Spain|publisher=UEFA|first=Lucy|last=Turner|date=15 October 2007|accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref> However, he failed to make the final cut for the final stages, where the nation emerged victorious.\n\nRiera was again called to the squad in October 2008 for two [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifiers]] after Sevilla's [[Diego Capel]] withdrew with an injury, and played 12 minutes in a 3\u20130 victory in [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.farodevigo.es/deportes/2008/10/12/espana-supera-problemas-estonia-0-3-goles-juanito-villa-puyol/265524.html|title=Espa\u00f1a sale inmaculada de Estonia|trans-title=Spain leave Estonia unscathed|newspaper=[[Faro de Vigo]]|first=Roberto|last=Morales|language=Spanish|date=12 October 2008|access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> In the following year, on 1 April, he netted a [[Last-minute goal|last-minute winner]] in [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] (2\u20131).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/matches/season=2010/round=15218/match=302466/index.html|title=Riera takes the wind out of Turkey's sails|publisher=UEFA|date=1 April 2009|accessdate=10 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nManager [[Vicente del Bosque]] named Riera in the squad for the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]], and he played in four matches for the third-placed team. He was, however, overlooked for the World Cup squad in South Africa, as the national side were crowned champions.\n\n==Personal life==\nRiera's younger brother, [[Sito Riera|Sito]], is also a footballer. He too represented Espanyol, but only [[RCD Espanyol B|their reserves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futbolbalear.es/2010/08/11/sito-riera-me-gustaria-jugar-en-el-mallorca/|title=Sito Riera: \"Me gustar\u00eda jugar en el Mallorca\"|trans-title=Sito Riera: \u201cI would like to play with Mallorca\u201d|publisher=F\u00fatbol Balear|language=Spanish|date=11 August 2010|accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Sources:<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/albert-riera-ortega/3647/|title=Riera|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=11729&cc=5739|title=Alberto Riera|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=15 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324184201/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=11729&cc=5739|archivedate=24 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tff.org/Default.aspx?pageId=30&kisiId=1432237|title=Albert Riera Ortega|publisher=[[Turkish Football Federation]]|accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]]\n|[[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1999\u20132000]]\n|7||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||1\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2000\u201301]]\n|31||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||31||6\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2001\u201302]]\n|16||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||5\n|-\n!Total\n!54!!12!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!54!!12\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n|[[2000\u201301 La Liga|2000\u201301]]\n|2||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||1\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 La Liga|2001\u201302]]\n|7||1||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||0||13||2\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 La Liga|2002\u201303]]\n|35||4||5||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||40||4\n|-\n!Total\n!46!!6!!7!!1!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!3!!0!!56!!7\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]]\n|[[2003\u201304 Ligue 1|2003\u201304]]\n|32||2||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||5||44||7\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305]]\n|21||2||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||23||2\n|-\n!Total\n!53!!4!!4!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!10!!5!!67!!9\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]]\n|[[2005\u201306 La Liga|2005\u201306]]\n|8|