*[[S\u00fcper Lig]]: [[2011\u201312 S\u00fcper Lig|2011\u201312]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2012/05/12/actualidad/1336847770_786081.html|title=El Galatasaray, campe\u00f3n de la liga turca|trans-title=Galatasaray, Turkish league champions|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|language=Spanish|date=12 May 2012|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref> [[2012\u201313 S\u00fcper Lig|2012\u201313]]<ref name=SW/>\n*[[Turkish Super Cup]]: [[2012 Turkish Super Cup|2012]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.turkiyegazetesi.com.tr/futbol/20004.aspx|title=Galatasaray: 3 \u2013 Fenerbah\u00e7e: 2|newspaper=[[T\u00fcrkiye (newspaper)|T\u00fcrkiye]]|language=Turkish|date=12 August 2012|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Spain'''\n*[[FIFA Confederations Cup]] third place: [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8118574.stm|title=Spain 3\u20132 South Africa (aet)|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 June 2009|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{BDFutbol}}\n* {{Lequipe}}\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* [http://www.lfchistory.net/player_profile.asp?player_id=1201 Liverpool historic profile]\n* {{NFT player}}\n* {{FIFA player}}\n* {{UEFA player}}<!--uses Wikidata-->\n\n{{Spain squad 2009 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riera, Albert}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Manacor]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Balearic footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:RCD Espanyol footballers]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:FC Girondins de Bordeaux players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:S\u00fcper Lig players]]\n[[Category:Galatasaray S.K. footballers]]\n[[Category:Udinese Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Slovenian PrvaLiga players]]\n[[Category:NK Zavr\u010d players]]\n[[Category:FC Koper players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:2009 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Greece]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Slovenia]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the former Spain international footballer|another Spanish footballer|Albert Riera (footballer, born 1983)}}\n{{Spanish name|Riera|Ortega}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Albert Riera\n| image = 1 albert riera 2017.jpg\n| caption = Riera playing a friendly with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2017\n| fullname = Albert Riera Ortega<ref>{{cite web|url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=26921|title=Acta del partido celebrado el 10 de mayo de 2015, en Palma de Mallorca|trans-title=Minutes of the match held on 10 May 2015, in Palma de Mallorca|publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]]|language=Spanish|date=10 May 2015|accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|4|15|df=y}}<ref name=Profile>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/envivos/fichas/1/166/4262.html|title=Albert RIERA Ortega|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Manacor]], Spain<ref name=Profile/>\n| height = 1.87 m<ref name=Profile/>\n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]], [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]]\n| currentclub =\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1999\u20132000 | youthclubs1 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n| years1 = 2000\u20132002 | clubs1 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] | caps1 = 54 | goals1 = 12\n| years2 = 2001\u20132003 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps2 = 46 | goals2 = 6\n| years3 = 2003\u20132005 | clubs3 = [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] | caps3 = 53 | goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2005\u20132008 | clubs4 = [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] | caps4 = 72 | goals4 = 8\n| years5 = 2006 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] (loan) | caps5 = 15 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2008\u20132010 | clubs6 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] | caps6 = 40 | goals6 = 3\n| years7 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs7 = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] | caps7 = 26 | goals7 = 6\n| years8 = 2011\u20132014 | clubs8 = [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] | caps8 = 60 | goals8 = 3\n| years9 = 2014 | clubs9 = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] | caps9 = 8 | goals9 = 1\n| years10 = 2014 | clubs10 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] | caps10 = 0 | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2015 | clubs11 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps11 = 6 | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 2015 | clubs12 = [[NK Zavr\u010d|Zavr\u010d]] | caps12 = 12 | goals12 = 1\n| years13 = 2016 | clubs13 = [[FC Koper|Koper]] | caps13 = 1 | goals13 = 0\n| totalcaps = 393 | totalgoals = 45\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\u20132001 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 11 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2002\u20132003 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps2 = 15 | nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2007\u20132009 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps3 = 16 | nationalgoals3 = 4\n}}\n'''Albert Riera Ortega''' (born 15 April 1982) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played mainly as a [[Midfielder#Winger|left winger]] but also as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]].\n\nHe made a name for himself at [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] (where he won one [[Copa del Rey]] and reached one [[2007 UEFA Cup Final|UEFA Cup final]]) and also played professionally in France, England, Greece, Turkey, Italy and Slovenia, notably spending three years with [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]].\n\nRiera won 16 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Spain national football team|Spain]], representing the nation at the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009 Confederations Cup]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Mallorca===\nBorn in [[Manacor]], [[Balearic Islands]], Riera started his professional career with hometown club [[RCD Mallorca]], but could only make a combined ten [[La Liga]] appearances in his first two seasons.\n\nIn the [[2002\u201303 La Liga|2002\u201303 campaign]], already an undisputed starter, he helped the local team to [[2002\u201303 Copa del Rey|the conquest]] of the [[Copa del Rey]],<ref name=COPA>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/06/29/deportes/1056837603_850215.html|title=Eto'o pone Mallorca a brindar|trans-title=Eto'o has Mallorca toasting|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|first=Jos\u00e9|last=Miguelez|language=Spanish|date=29 June 2003|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> and scored four league goals in 35 games.<ref name=Mirror>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/most-popular/2008/08/29/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-new-liverpool-signing-albert-riera-115875-20716276/|title=10 things you need to know about new Liverpool signing Albert Riera|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|first=Dan|last=Silver|date=29 August 2008|accessdate=1 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614145034/http://www.mirror.co.uk/most-popular/2008/08/29/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-new-liverpool-signing-albert-riera-115875-20716276/|archivedate=14 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Bordeaux===\nIn the summer of 2003, Riera moved to [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=86920.html|title=Riera raring to go at Bordeaux|publisher=UEFA|date=31 July 2003|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref> where he was a first-team regular for two years.\n\nHe made 66 competitive appearances for the [[Ligue 1]] side, and netted nine times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football365.fr/espagnols-de-ligue-1-diapo-2653871.html#item=1|title=Les espagnols de la Ligue 1 [Diapo]|trans-title=The Ligue 1 Spaniards [Diapo]|publisher=Football 365|language=French|date=8 August 2016|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Espanyol===\nRiera returned to Spain in 2005, when he signed for [[RCD Espanyol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=315451.html|title=Riera wings into Espanyol|publisher=UEFA|date=7 July 2005|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref> In [[2005\u201306 La Liga|his first season]] he played only eight league matches, prompting a January 2006 loan move to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=382387.html|title=City tempt Riera to England|publisher=UEFA|date=5 January 2006|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref> where he was also unable to establish himself, scoring against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in a 3\u20130 home win on 1 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4657216.stm|title=Man City 3\u20130 Newcastle|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=1 February 2006|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nRiera returned to [[Catalonia]] prior to [[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]]. During that season, Espanyol [[2006\u201307 UEFA Cup|reached]] [[2007 UEFA Cup Final|the final]] of the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] at [[Hampden Park]], Glasgow, where they played fellow Spaniards [[Sevilla FC]]: he scored to level the game at 1\u20131, but his team eventually lost 1\u20133 on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]].<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6657065.stm|title=Espanyol 2\u20132 Sevilla|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Charlie|last=Henderson|date=16 May 2007|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> At the end of the campaign, he extended his contract until 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2007/08/23/mas_futbol/1187820012_850215.html|title=Riera prolonga su contrato con el Espanyol hasta el 2011|trans-title=Riera extends his contract with Espanyol until 2011|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|language=Spanish|date=23 August 2007|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Liverpool===\n[[File:2009-3-14 ManUtd vs LFC Ronaldo Tackling cropped.JPG|thumb|upright|Riera (left) in action for Liverpool.]]\nOn 1 September 2008 (transfer deadline day), Riera signed a four-year deal with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] for a fee of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]8 million, being given the number 11 shirt.<ref name=Mirror/> He made his [[Premier League]] debut on the 13th, playing 71 minutes of a 2\u20131 home win against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/7601885.stm|title=Liverpool 2\u20131 Man Utd|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Mandeep|last=Sanghera|date=13 September 2008|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref> and scored his first goal for the Reds as they beat [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] 3\u20132 on 18 October,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7665090.stm|title=Liverpool 3\u20132 Wigan|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Russell|last=Barder|date=18 October 2008|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> adding another in [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|the group stage]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]] in a 3\u20131 victory at [[PSV Eindhoven]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7763223.stm|title=PSV 1\u20133 Liverpool|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Ian|last=Hughes|date=9 December 2008|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nRiera netted Liverpool's first goal of 2009, and also scored in [[2008\u201309 FA Cup|the third round]] in the [[FA Cup]] on 3 January, against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/7803324.stm|title=Preston 0\u20132 Liverpool|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Mark|last=Ashenden|date=3 January 2009|accessdate=22 September 2009}}</ref> Later during [[2008\u201309 Premier League|that season]] he scored against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in a 5\u20130 home rout on 22 March 2009, through a half-volley after [[Pepe Reina]]'s long [[goal kick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7937107.stm|title=Liverpool 5\u20130 Aston Villa|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Phil|last=McNulty|date=22 March 2009|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2010, Riera was suspended after comments made to the Spanish press regarding his first team opportunities and the approach of Liverpool manager [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]]. The player was quoted as saying: \"He's never sorted out a situation with a player by talking with him.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8574001.stm|title=Rafael Benitez keen to offload outspoken Albert Riera|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 March 2010|accessdate=28 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325093806/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8574001.stm|archivedate=25 March 2010}}</ref> He was transfer listed following the comments, with Russian clubs [[PFC CSKA Moscow]] and [[FC Spartak Moscow]] thought to be interested in a permanent move.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rafael-benitez-banishes-vocal-albert-riera-vn7h67wkg7r|title=Rafael Benitez banishes vocal Albert Riera|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=19 March 2010|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> On the 23rd of that month it was announced that Liverpool had accepted a \u00a36 million bid from CSKA for the player;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/mar/23/albert-riera-rafael-benitez-liverpool-transfer|title=Liverpool accept \u00a36m offer from CSKA Moscow for Albert Riera|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|first=Andy|last=Hunter|date=24 March 2010|accessdate=28 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324193143/http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2010/mar/23/albert-riera-rafael-benitez-liverpool-transfer|archivedate=24 March 2010}}</ref> however, it appeared to be solely rumours, any interest was officially denied<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=761284&sec=transfers&cc=5739|title=CSKA deny interest in Albert Riera|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=28 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402070914/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=761284&sec=transfers&cc=5739|archivedate=2 April 2010}}</ref>\u2013 additionally, the player's agent, \u00c1ngel Castells, confirmed that only Spartak had made a proposal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/Benitez/subasta/Riera/elpepidep/20100327elpepidep_6/Tes|title=Ben\u00edtez 'subasta' a Riera|trans-title=Ben\u00edtez 'auctions' Riera|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|first=Jordi|last=Quixano|language=Spanish|date=27 March 2010|accessdate=28 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Olympiacos===\nOn 23 July 2010, Riera joined Greek club [[Olympiacos F.C.]] on a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8843423.stm|title=Liverpool winger Albert Riera completes Olympiakos move|publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 July 2010|accessdate=23 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723133030/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8843423.stm|archivedate=23 July 2010}}</ref> The deal was reported to be worth around [[Euro|\u20ac]]6 million (\u20ac4 million plus another potential \u20ac2&nbsp;million in bonuses), with a salary of around \u20ac2.5&nbsp;million per season; he became one of the most expensive transfers in the country's history, as he reunited with former Espanyol manager [[Ernesto Valverde]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1549/rest-of-europe/2010/07/23/2039025/breaking-news-official-olympiacos-sign-albert-riera-from|title=Official: Olympiacos sign Albert Riera from Liverpool|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Adam|last=Scime|date=23 July 2010|accessdate=23 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725014848/http://www.goal.com/en/news/1549/rest-of-europe/2010/07/23/2039025/breaking-news-official-olympiacos-sign-albert-riera-from|archivedate=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nRiera scored his first goal for Olympiacos against [[Kerkyra F.C.]] in a 2\u20130 home win, and appeared in more than 30 official games during [[2010\u201311 Superleague Greece|the season]] as the [[Piraeus]] team won the [[Superleague Greece|Superleague]].\n\n===Galatasaray===\n[[File:Riera.JPG|left|thumb|180px|Riera playing for Galatasaray against [[Ankaragucu|Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc]] (2012).]]\nOn 3 September 2011, Riera completed a \u20ac3 million move to Turkish giants [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray SK]], signing a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/es/news/21/fichajes/2011/09/03/2648808/es-oficial-el-galatasaray-ficha-a-albert-riera|title=Es oficial: El Galatasaray ficha a Albert Riera|trans-title=It's official: Galatasaray sign Albert Riera|publisher=Goal|language=Spanish|date=3 September 2011|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goal in the [[S\u00fcper Lig]] on 25 January 2012 in a 4\u20130 home defeat of [[MKE Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc]], and was an habitual first-choice in [[2011\u201312 S\u00fcper Lig|his first season]] as the [[Istanbul]]-based team won the national championship; he was also involved, however, in a punching session with teammate [[Felipe Melo]] just before the playoffs started.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/melo-riera-brawl-overshadows-last-week-in-the-super-league.aspx?pageID=238&nID=17843&NewsCatID=362|title=Melo-Riera brawl overshadows last week in the Super League|newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]]|date=7 April 2012|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the arrival of prospect [[Nordin Amrabat]] for the [[2012\u201313 S\u00fcper Lig|2012\u201313 campaign]], Riera was reconverted by manager [[Fatih Terim]] into an attacking [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]], mainly due to the lack of options in the position other than injury-prone [[Hakan Balta]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/03/29/en/football/real_madrid/1364512402.html|title=\"Galatasaray fans win games\"|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|first=Juan Ignacio|last=Garc\u00eda-Ochoa|date=29 March 2013|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> On 28 January 2014, he agreed to have his contract terminated for \u20ac750,000 and left the [[T\u00fcrk Telekom Stadium|Ali Sami Yen Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccernews.com/riera-amrabat-leave-galatasaray/136985/|title=Riera, Amrabat leave Galatasaray|publisher=Soccer News|first=Nemanja|last=Lazarevic|date=28 January 2014|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nOn 24 March 2014, Riera signed a pre-contract with Italian side [[Udinese Calcio]], effective as of 1 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udinese.it/portal/IT/handle/?hil&page=redazione_approfondimenti&vid=2312|title=Primo tassello per la prossima stagione: ha firmato Albert Riera Ortega|trans-title=First piece for next season: Albert Riera Ortega has signed|publisher=Udinese Calcio|language=Italian|date=24 March 2014|accessdate=24 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324190225/http://www.udinese.it/portal/IT/handle/?hil&page=redazione_approfondimenti&vid=2312|archivedate=24 March 2014}}</ref> Three days later, he joined [[Football League Championship]]'s [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] until the end of [[2013\u201314 Football League Championship|the season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/watford-sign-former-liverpool-and-spain-winger-albert-riera-on-until-the-end-of-season-9219203.html|title=Watford sign former Liverpool and Spain winger Albert Riera on until the end of season|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nRiera scored his first and only goal for Watford on 19 April 2014, in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26998629|title=Watford 3\u20131 Ipswich|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 April 2014|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> He had an extended run until late in the month, when he was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] for two bookable offences in a 1\u20133 loss at [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Chartlton Athletic]] after a high challenge on [[Diego Poyet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140429-charlton-match-report-1518040.aspx|title=Match report: Charlton Athletic 3\u20131 Watford|publisher=Watford F.C|date=29 April 2014|accessdate=18 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617183228/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140429-charlton-match-report-1518040.aspx|archivedate=17 June 2014}}</ref> After the match, he was charged by [[The Football Association]] for improper conduct, having confronted the officials and having to be dragged away by his team-mates;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11686/9291696/watford-winger-albert-riera-faces-fa-misconduct-charge-over-reaction-to-red-card|title=Watford winger Albert Riera faces FA misconduct charge over reaction to red card|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=1 May 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> he was given a two-match ban although only one remained to end the campaign,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/sport/11193325.Riera_handed_additional_one_match_suspension/|title=Watford's Albert Riera handed additional one-match ban by the FA for his conduct following his red card against Charlton Athletic|newspaper=[[Watford Observer]]|date=6 May 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> and he subsequently returned to Udinese.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140604-released-players-announcement-1602043.aspx|title=Official: Released players confirmed|publisher=Watford F.C|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617184821/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140604-released-players-announcement-1602043.aspx|archivedate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 November 2014, Riera was sacked by Udinese for attending a [[poker tournament]] rather than reporting to play against [[A.C. ChievoVerona]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Udinese/24-11-2014/udinese-albert-riera-asso-poker-secondo-un-torneo-mentre-compagni-pareggiano-col-chievo-10040405691.shtml|title=Udinese, Albert Riera, il calciatore dimenticato che vince a poker|trans-title=Udinese, Albert Riera, the forgotten player who wins at poker|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|language=Italian|date=24 November 2014|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2284157-ex-liverpool-man-albert-riera-sacked-by-udinese-after-missing-game-to-play-poker|title=Ex-Liverpool man Albert Riera sacked by Udinese after missing game to play poker|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|first=Mark|last=Patterson|date=30 November 2014|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref> also taking to [[Twitter]] to insult the organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calcioweb.eu/2014/11/udinese-riera-cacciato-via-insultava-la-squadra-su-twitter-e-giocava-poker-durante-le-partite/150706/|title=Udinese \u2013 Riera cacciato via: insultava la squadra su Twitter e giocava a poker durante le partite|trans-title=Udinese \u2013 Riera gets the boot: insulting squad on Twitter and playing poker during match|publisher=Calcio Web|first=Giuseppe|last=Mazza|date=29 November 2014|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref> He returned to his first club Mallorca the following 5 March, after agreeing to a one-and-a-half year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=34094&idmenu=3|title=Riera vuelve a casa|trans-title=Riera returns home|publisher=RCD Mallorca|language=Spanish|date=5 March 2015|accessdate=15 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402190016/http://rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=34094&idmenu=3|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> In May, he was subjected to disciplinary proceedings after claiming he would not appear again for the team as long as [[Miquel Soler]] was the manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2015/05/19/futbol/equipos/mallorca/1432033628.html|title=El Mallorca abre expediente a Riera por \"grave indisciplina\"|trans-title=Mallorca start disciplinary proceedings on Riera for \"severe breach of discipline\"|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=19 May 2015|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 2015, Slovenian sports newspaper [[Ekipa (Slovenia)|''Ekipa'']] reported that Riera would sign a contract with [[NK Zavr\u010d]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ekipa24.si/clanek/nogomet/prva-liga/55f2caaedd306/zavrc-koper-senzacija-prihaja-nekdanji-spanski-reprezentant|title=Zavrc \u2013 Koper: Senzacija! Prihaja nekdanji spanski reprezentant|trans-title=Zavrc \u2013 Koper: Surprise! Former Spanish international arrives|newspaper=[[Ekipa (Slovenia)|Ekipa]]|language=Slovenian|date=11 September 2015|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> Three days later, he was officially presented.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ekipa24.si/clanek/nogomet/prva-liga/55f84490a6d90/ekskluzivno-ce-niste-verjeli-zdaj-morate-riera-na-treningu-v-zavrcu|title=Riera v dresu Zavr\u010da|trans-title=Riera in Zavrc's jersey|newspaper=Ekipa|language=Slovenian|date=15 September 2015|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nRiera terminated his contract on 22 January 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtvslo.si/sport/nogomet/riera-sporazumno-zapusca-zavrc/384016|title=Riera sporazumno zapu\u0161\u010da Zavr\u010d|trans-title=Riera is leaving Zavrc after mutual contract termination|publisher=[[RTV Slovenija]]|author=S.J.|language=Slovenian|date=22 January 2016|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> but remained in the country as he joined [[FC Koper]] until June 2018 shortly after.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nogomania.com/Slovenski-Nogomet/Ekipa/Koper/Novica/Rieri-pogodba-kar-do-leta-2018.aspx|title=Rieri pogodba kar do leta 2018|trans-title=Riera signed until 2018|publisher=Nogomania|author=Uredni\u0161tvo|language=Slovenian|date=26 January 2016|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> He was released in July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://snportal.si/prva-liga/riera-ni-vec-clan-kopra/|title=Riera ni ve\u010d \u010dlan Kopra|trans-title=Riera is no longer a member of Koper|publisher=SN Portal|first=Peter|last=Dominko|language=Slovenian|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nRiera officially announced his retirement from football on 24 January 2018, through a social media post portraying himself having literally hung up his boots on a tree.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/01/24/primera/1516815671_549262.html|title=Albert Riera se retira del f\u00fatbol: \"Es hora de decir adi\u00f3s\"|trans-title=Albert Riera retires from football: \"It's time to say goodbye\"|newspaper=Diario AS|language=Spanish|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nRiera made his debut for the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]] on 13 October 2007 in an [[UEFA Euro 2008]] [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying|qualifier]] against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]], and scored from outside the box in a 3\u20131 away win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/289897/0/victoria/seleccion/dinamarca/|title=Espa\u00f1a sale del t\u00fanel tras su triunfo en Dinamarca (1\u20133)|trans-title=Spain exit tunnel after win in Denmark (1\u20133)|newspaper=[[20 minutos]]|language=Spanish|date=13 October 2007|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=603234.html#espanyol+flag+spain|title=Espanyol fly flag for Spain|publisher=UEFA|first=Lucy|last=Turner|date=15 October 2007|accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref> However, he failed to make the final cut for the final stages, where the nation emerged victorious.\n\nRiera was again called to the squad in October 2008 for two [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifiers]] after Sevilla's [[Diego Capel]] withdrew with an injury, and played 12 minutes in a 3\u20130 victory in [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.farodevigo.es/deportes/2008/10/12/espana-supera-problemas-estonia-0-3-goles-juanito-villa-puyol/265524.html|title=Espa\u00f1a sale inmaculada de Estonia|trans-title=Spain leave Estonia unscathed|newspaper=[[Faro de Vigo]]|first=Roberto|last=Morales|language=Spanish|date=12 October 2008|access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> In the following year, on 1 April, he netted a [[Last-minute goal|last-minute winner]] in [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] (2\u20131).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/matches/season=2010/round=15218/match=302466/index.html|title=Riera takes the wind out of Turkey's sails|publisher=UEFA|date=1 April 2009|accessdate=10 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nManager [[Vicente del Bosque]] named Riera in the squad for the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]], and he played in four matches for the third-placed team. He was, however, overlooked for the World Cup squad in South Africa, as the national side were crowned champions.\n\n==Personal life==\nRiera's younger brother, [[Sito Riera|Sito]], is also a footballer. He too represented Espanyol, but only [[RCD Espanyol B|their reserves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futbolbalear.es/2010/08/11/sito-riera-me-gustaria-jugar-en-el-mallorca/|title=Sito Riera: \"Me gustar\u00eda jugar en el Mallorca\"|trans-title=Sito Riera: \u201cI would like to play with Mallorca\u201d|publisher=F\u00fatbol Balear|language=Spanish|date=11 August 2010|accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Sources:<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/albert-riera-ortega/3647/|title=Riera|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=11729&cc=5739|title=Alberto Riera|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=15 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324184201/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=11729&cc=5739|archivedate=24 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tff.org/Default.aspx?pageId=30&kisiId=1432237|title=Albert Riera Ortega|publisher=[[Turkish Football Federation]]|accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]]\n|[[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1999\